<statement>
<p>
Determine whether the following four statements are true or false. Explain your answers.
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
<p>
 <m>\exists x\in\mathbb{Z} \text{ s.t. } \exists y\in\mathbb{Z} \text{ s.t. } x+y=3</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>\exists x\in\mathbb{Z} \text{ s.t. } \forall y\in\mathbb{Z}, x+y=3</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>\forall x\in\mathbb{Z}, \exists y\in\mathbb{Z} \text{ s.t. } x+y=3</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>\forall x\in\mathbb{Z}, \forall y\in\mathbb{Z},  x+y=3</m>.
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<hint>
<p>
If you are unsure if the statement is true or not, then explore its negation <mdash/> it might be easier to understand.
</p>
</hint>
<solution>
<p>
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
<p>
 True. We just need to find one example of <m>x,y</m> so that <m>x+y=3</m>. So take <m>x=0,y=3</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 False. We show the negation is true; the negation is <m>\forall x \in \mathbb{Z}, \exists y\in \mathbb{Z} \text{ s.t. } x+y \neq 3</m>. We must be careful to choose <m>x</m> before we choose <m>y</m>. So, let <m>x</m> be any integer, and then set <m>y=-x</m>. Then <m>x+y = 0 \neq 3</m>. Since the negation is true, the original is false.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 True. Let <m>x</m> be any integer and then pick <m>y=3-x</m>. Then <m>x+y=3</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 False. We show the negation is true; the negation is <m>\exists x\in \mathbb{Z} \text{ s.t. }  \exists y\in \mathbb{Z} \text{ s.t. } x+y \neq 3</m>. So we only need one example of <m>x,y</m> so that <m>x+y \neq 3</m>. Pick <m>x=3,y=7</m> then <m>x+y \neq 3</m>. Since the negation is true, the original is false.
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>
</exercise>